  "prompt": "What does white smoke from motorcycle exhaust mean?",
  "response": "White smoke from a motorcycle exhaust can indicate several potential issues:\n\n1. Normal Condensation\n- In cold weather, white steam is normal and will dissipate quickly\n- Typically harmless and not a cause for concern\n\n2. Coolant Leak\n- Thick, continuous white smoke suggests coolant is leaking into combustion chamber\n- Possible causes include:\n- Blown head gasket\n- Cracked engine block\n- Damaged cylinder head\n- Requires immediate professional inspection\n\n3. Incorrect Fuel/Oil Mixture\n- In two-stroke engines, white smoke can indicate incorrect fuel-to-oil ratio\n- May cause engine damage if not addressed\n\n4. Water in Combustion Chamber\n- Can result from improper engine storage or exposure to moisture\n- Requires draining and potential repairs\n\n5. Worn Piston Rings or Valve Seals\n- Can cause oil to leak into combustion chamber\n- Leads to white or bluish-white smoke\n- Indicates potential internal engine wear\n\n6. Low-Quality Fuel\n- Poor fuel quality can cause incomplete combustion\n- May result in temporary white smoke\n\nRecommendations:\n- If white smoke persists, consult a professional mechanic\n- Avoid continuing to ride with significant exhaust smoke\n- Regular maintenance can prevent many exhaust smoke issues",
